Many microspheres (named “hot-nodes”) with different sizes appear in the 2D microsheets ( Fig. 1 a, stage iii) as the reaction proceeds further. After Oswald ripening, these “hot-nodes” became larger but relatively uniform ( Fig. 1 a, stage iv). Later, these “hot-nodes” continue to grow and aggregate the surrounding Gd3+/CA complexes ( Fig. 1 a, stage v). Finally, 3D Gd-MNs having well connected stick-like junction are formed as can be seen from Fig. 1 a, stage vi. SEM images ( Fig. 1 c and d) clearly show that Gd-MNs have a spatially well-defined 3D network structure of millimeter size. The size of a typical 3D Gd-MNs can reach up to 0.7 mm at length × 0.5 mm at width (
Figure S3
). Further observation ( Fig. 1 e and f) reveals that these “hot-nodes” of the network with about 12 μm are well connected with a stick-like junction.

