Figure S5
) of P-Gd-MNs are very similar to that of Gd-MNs, suggesting no obvious difference in their structure.

Furthermore, we focus on the nature of FL enhancement. The extinction coefficient of CA molecule is lower due to the existence of only n-π* transition ( Fig. 3 c). Thus, CA molecules can only emit weak blue FL even at high concentrations and show excitation-dependent FL emission (see
Figure S7
). On the other hand, Gd3+/CA complex cannot emit sharp FL signals of Gd3+ ions by antenna effect. This is due to the high excited-state energy level of Gd3+ ions [15]. Therefore, the FL of Gd3+/CA complex originates from CA molecules. The FL of Gd3+/CA complex is still not very strong, but the emission is red-shifted compared to that of CA molecules (
Figure S8
).

So, it is inferred that the coordination of CA with Gd3+ ions increases the degree of conjugation [31–33]. However, Gd-MNs show obvious hyperchromic effect compared to CA and Gd3+/CA complex ( Fig. 3 c) [34]. This hyperchromic effect can be attributed to the formation of Gd-MNs as the conjugate structure between carboxylic ions and Gd3+ is greatly enhanced. The formation of conjugated structure is further proved by the red-shifted emission of Gd-MNs ( Fig. 3 d and
Figure S9
). The QY of Gd-MNs is 152-folds compared to Gd3+/CA complex. The reason behind this is the significant hyperchromic effect which showing a special HEF phenomenon. In the case of P-Gd-MNs, the internal conjugate structure is partially destroyed due to the existence of porous structure which consequently decreases the FL.

To further soften the light of P-WLEDs, we embed fluorescent carbon dots (CDs), having long-wavelength emission, into the porous structure of P-Gd-MNs. The CDs are synthesized from R6G and TETA, as the –NH2 groups of TETA can bind the CA residues on the porous surfaces of P-Gd-MNs. By adjusting the TETA content, we obtained CDs@P-Gd-MNs with different emissions (

                        Figure S12-S14

                     ). This strategy can be employed for the fabrication of a series of WLEDs from cold white light to warm white light, including CDs-1@P-WLEDs with a CCT of 6866 K (neutral WLEDs), CDs-2@P-WLEDs with a CCT of 4514 K (warm WLEDs), and CDs-3@P-WLEDs

R6G is used as a model dye for the investigation of the catalytical activity of Cu@P-Gd-MNs. It is found that R6G can emit strong FL at 560 nm with an excitation-independent FL emission (
Figure S16
). The catalytical efficiency is closely related to the content of Cu@P-Gd-MNs. The catalytic efficiency gradually increases along with the increase in amount of Cu@P-Gd-MNs. In the case of 100 mg Cu@P-Gd-MNs, the catalytical efficiency reaches 67% and is maintained at a relatively stable level (
Figure S17
). Moreover, catalytic efficiency can be significantly improved by increasing the amount of H2O2 (
Figure S18
). When the concentration of H2O2 is higher than 21%, R6G can be rapidly degraded. The R6G can be degraded within 60 min when a suitable concentration of H2O2 and enough Cu@P-Gd-MNs are used. The time-dependent degradation rate is shown in Fig. 5 c. The catalytic mechanism of Cu@P-Gd-MNs is investigated by electron spin resonance (ESR). H2O2 only produces a small amount of free radicals in the presence of P-Gd-MNs (
Figure S19
). However, Cu@P-Gd-MNs have a better catalytical activity that can accelerate the decomposition of H2O2 to yield a large number of •O2 − and •OH radicals, thereby accelerating the R6G degradation ( Fig. 5 d and e). Compared with other peroxidase-like catalysts (Table S4), Cu@P-Gd-MNs show excellent peroxidase-like catalytical activity with short degradation time.
